         <children>
            <Text fill="WHITE" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="You may have heard &quot;distribution&quot; thrown around when it comes to operating systems or more specifically, GNU/Linux; but what is a distro?&#10;&#10;GNU/Linux isn't like Windows or Mac OS where there is only one release and each one gets more updated. You can pick Windows 10 over Windows 7 but they are the same, just one being more updated than the latter.&#10;&#10;With GNU/Linux, you don't have just one version, different organisations and people work on different parts.&#10;&#10;GNU and Linux are open source, meaning people can use and modify them. &#10;&#10;You can get GNU, the Linux Kernel, and many other tools to compile them to create your own operating system but that takes a lot of time, that's why people do it for you.&#10;&#10;Each operating system made up with GNU/Linux, whilst being similar, is different. &#10;&#10;Some examples of GNU/Linux distros are:&#10;&#10;Ubuntu, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora, Debian, and Linux Mint." wrappingWidth="471.0" VBox.vgrow="ALWAYS">
