            <Text fill="WHITE" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="So why are there different distributions and not just one open source one?&#10;&#10;Different people have different ideas. The Fedora operating system refuses to include any closed source software. Other operating systems, such as Linux Mint, include some closed source software because it makes some things easier for users, such as accessing media.&#10;&#10;Some distros are forks of already existing ones. Ubuntu is an operating system in which at it's core is Debian, but it's been modified and made easier for general users to use. There are many distributions like this because it saves time making your own from scratch, or you like the pre-existing operating system but you just want to change a couple of things. &#10;&#10;They also include different software, Ubuntu will look different to Linux Mint. They'll each have their own package manager (this'll be covered later), in short a different way to install and update their software.&#10;&#10;If you don't understand, it's kind of like a Samsung smart phone compared to a Sony smart phone. They are both running on Android with the Linux Kernel but they both look different and include different apps (like text messengers)." wrappingWidth="470.0">
